data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages. Here's the modernized version using MSTest 3.x+ collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Before | After | Why |
|--------|-------|-----|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" vs "expected True, got False" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | Remove — `Single()` already throws if missing | Redundant check |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` assertion is fine with `Assert.IsTrue` since there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" method. If you want a clearer failure message there, you could loop:

```csharp
foreach (var user in users)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(user.IsActive, $"User {user.Name} was not active");
}
```
